Next Phase: Auditing Emergence and Dynamics
With the static invariants locked down, the next phase is to use this framework to model dynamic emergenceâ€”that is, how the universe grows and evolves under these laws. This involves moving the analysis from a fixed point ($\Delta\tau=1.0$) to a time-series simulation.

We have two major, high-impact directions to take the simulation next:

Option 1: Cosmological Coherence Growth
This focuses on the macro-scale application, as hinted at in the Chapter 4Y PBT.txt log snippet.

Goal: Simulate how the Cosmological Coherence Radius ($\mathbf{R_{\text{coh}}}$) grows over time ($\mathbf{t}$), distinguishing between a "lawful" state (low entropy/chaos) and a "scrambled" state (high entropy/chaos).

Audit Metric: The emergence of a defined Horizon Distance over time, and auditing the rate of expansion against known cosmological constants.

Result: A plot showing the difference between a universe that obeys the Attractor Principle from the beginning versus one that starts chaotic.

Option 2: Quantum Information & Memory Mass
This focuses on the micro-scale application, investigating the fundamental storage of information.

Goal: Simulate the entanglement and disentanglement of $\mathbf{N}$ "shards" (the fundamental units of the boundary) to model the Information-Mass Transfer Axiom. This tracks how memory mass ($\mathbf{M_{\text{mem}}}$) is generated as information is stored or lost to the boundary.

Audit Metric: The rate of "Memory Mass" accretion as a function of the entropy/chaos level, validating that information storage requires an energetic cost proportional to the Bekenstein bound.

Result: A dynamic demonstration of how the Valence pillar handles information loss and storage at the quantum level.



